# Real-time Streaming Pipeline using Kafka, Databricks, and Snowflake

# 1\. Overview

I designed a real-time streaming application to monitor station-level changes using Citibike NYC's live data feeds. The pipeline integrates Apache Kafka, Databricks, and Snowflake to process and store the data efficiently, ensuring scalability and real-time performance.

# 2\. Data Collection

Sources:

* Station Status: [https://gbfs.lyft.com/gbfs/1.1/bkn/en/station\_status.json](https://gbfs.lyft.com/gbfs/1.1/bkn/en/station\_status.json)  
* Station Information: [https://gbfs.lyft.com/gbfs/1.1/bkn/en/station\_information.json](https://gbfs.lyft.com/gbfs/1.1/bkn/en/station\_information.json)

Data Volume:

* 1500+ stations across NYC generate data every minute.  
* Estimated daily volume: 2,160,000 rows, each row approximately 134 KB, totaling 289.44 MB/day.  
* As new stations and docks are deployed, data volume will scale proportionally.

#  3\. Kafka as a Staging Layer

* Chose Apache Kafka for managing the velocity and volume of real-time data streams.  
* Utilized Confluent’s managed Kafka with two topics:  
*   station\_status  
*   station\_information  
* Each topic was configured with 6 partitions. Kafka's round-robin partitioning strategy was used to distribute messages evenly across partitions, as the key was set to null.

## Set up Kafka Cluster in Confluent:

* Create a free account on Confluent Kafka with $400 free credits  
* Go to the Confluent Cloud website and sign in  
* In the nav bar on the left select Environments and Add environment or select Add New  
* Choose a cluster type, such as Basic, Standard, or Enterprise Dedicated  
* Select Begin configuration  
* Choose a cloud provider, region, and availability zone  
* Enter a cluster name, review the configuration and select Launch cluster  
* If a payment method hasn’t been set up, enter one and select Review or Skip payment

## Create topics:

* Select a cluster from the navigation bar and click the Topics menu. The Manage Topics Using Control Center for Confluent Platform opens.  
* Click Add a Topic.  
* Enter a unique topic name.  
* Select or type a custom number of partitions.  
* Click Create with defaults.

Use station\_information\_ingest.py & station\_status\_ingest.py to ingest data from Citybike API to Kafka topic

# 4\. Data Transformation using Databricks

* Kafka serves as a transient layer with a 7-day retention policy before data is moved to a lakehouse.  
* Databricks was selected as the processing platform, leveraging Delta tables and Spark for real-time data transformation.

## Transformation steps:

* Exploded the station list into rows of key-value pairs.  
* Flattened these rows into columns, representing station attributes.  
* Filtered messages to retain only the latest records based on the last\_updated timestamp to avoid redundancy.

## Batch Processing:

* Data was processed in 10-minute micro-batches to optimize Spark executor performance and prevent resource overload.  
* Added a batch\_run\_date partition key to improve query performance and retrieval efficiency.

## Create a Databricks account:

* Go to Databricks.com and on the top right click Try Databricks and a new account can be created for free for 15 days after that the account will be billed  
* You can use the Community version (single node cluster) or Professional Use.  
* If you select Professional Use select the cloud provider to provision the Spark cluster  
* Selected GCP for this project so the below directions are for that. But other cloud providers will also follow similar steps.  
* Once your account is created on Databricks you will be directed to a page that will take you to the cloud console. Select Subscribe to 14-day Databricks trial in the cloud console  
* Now your Databricks account is created. Sign into your new account using the link here  
* Databricks File System, Workspace and Cluster setup

## File System:

* Once your Databricks account is created, 3 folders will be auto-created in your respective cloud storage account.  
* These folders are for the unity catalog and storing the actual parquet or any other format of the raw data and the Delta table is just a pointer to this catalog in cloud storage.  
* Workspace Creation:  
* Login to your Databricks account linked here  
* The landing page will display your GCP project name, region and account status as running  
* On the top right corner, select Create Workspace and give it a name  
* Step 3 is a one-time setup. After that, you can click Open to start working in your workspace

## Cluster Setup

* In your workspace nav bar, click on Compute to setup Spark cluster  
* Click on Create Compute.  
* I went with Databricks RE 13.3 (Scala 2.12 and Spark 3.4.1) as I wanted to connect Databricks with Snowflake and Snowflake driver did not have support for Spark 3.5  
* Select the applicable Driver and Worker cluster memory. I kept the default selections.  
* Select Create Cluster  
* Click on the cluster and go to Libraries to install the appropriate drivers required for your application.  
* Follow the linked Snowflake Documentation under “Downloading and Installing Connector” to install and get access to the correct Maven coordinates for the drivers  
* Install confluent-kafka\[avro,json,protobuf\]\>=1.4.2 for reading Kafka schema to databricks

# 5\. Data Validation using Chispa

* Chispa, a Python library, was used for validating input and output schemas in Spark.  
* Chispa provides fast PySpark test helper methods and descriptive error messages, ensuring high-quality PySpark code through integration testing.

    
Key validation checks include:

* Column equality using chispa.column\_comparer.  
* Dataframe equality using chispa.dataframe\_comparer.

* The Chispa library takes sample input columns and compares them with expected output columns to ensure accurate data transformation.  
* A script for setting up Chispa and running pytest is available in the pyspark\_tests folder of the GitHub repository.

# 6\. Data Storage in Snowflake

* Snowflake was chosen for its seamless integration with Spark and support for querying and building interactive applications.  
* Data was written to two tables, partitioned by batch\_run\_date.  
* The use of a forEachBatch() function ensured that micro-batches were efficiently processed and written to the tables, reducing the load on Spark executors.

## Create Snowflake Account

* Created a default Snowflake account with GCP.  
* Created 2 tables in Snowflake for storing the data flowing from station\_status and station\_information topics from Kafka  
* The Create table scripts can be found in snowflake-scripts

#  7\. Data Visualization using Streamlit

* Streamlit was integrated with Snowflake to build an operational dashboard for real-time monitoring of bike distribution across NYC stations.  
* The dashboard is designed for the operations team, helping ensure stations have sufficient bikes and charging capabilities during peak times.  
* Future improvements could include an analytics dashboard to provide historical insights, enabling better decision-making for bike allocation based on seasonal demand.
